AS1: Some people argue that crimes should get different sentences depending on how likely it is that the criminal will be caught. More specifically, crimes of similar seriousness should get a longer sentence if it is a harder crime to detect.
AS2: Some people say that the major determinant of the sentence for a crime should be the sentence that the person deserves to receive given the seriousness of the crime he committed.
AJ1: I am someone who doesn't have opinions.
AJ2: I am personally invested in my views.
AJ3: I would be willing to take account of the views of others who believe things that are different than mine.
AJ4: It doesn't bother me that people hold views that differ from mine.
AJ5: Views that differ from mine could be just as valid as my own.
AJ6: I recognize that I don't know all the information that could inform my views.
AC1: If a suspect runs from the police, then he or she probably committed the crime.
AC2: A defendant should be found guilty if 11 out of 12 jurors vote guilty.
AC3: Too often jurors hesitate to convict someone who is guilty, out of pure sympathy.
AC4: In most cases where the accused presents a strong defense, it is only because of a good lawyer.
AC5: For serious crimes like murder, a defendant should be found guilty so long as there is a 90% chance that he committed the crime.
AC6: Defense lawyers don't really care about guilt or innocence; they are just in business to make money.
AC7: Generally, the police make an arrest only when they are sure about who committed the crime.
AC8: Many accident claims filed against insurance companies are phony.
AC9: If the grand jury recommends that a person be brought to trial, then he probably committed the crime.
AC10: Extenuating circumstances should not be considered -- if a person commits a crime, then that person should be punished.
AC11: If a majority of the evidence -- but not all of it -- suggests that the defendant committed the crime, the jury should vote not guilty.
AC12: If the defendant committed a victimless crime like gambling or possesion of marijuana, he should never be convicted.
AC13: Judges can be swayed by their policy preferences.
AC14: It is possible for a judge to be objective in his or her rulings and opinions.
